l financial institutions. Canada has been outspoken about the violation of rights in countries ruled by communist regimes, while hesitation and ambiguity are a feature of Canadian policies toward South Africa and Central America, as well as in lending policies to international financial institutions, Canadian development assistance, and Canadian arms sales. Each of these areas is examined in Human Rights in Canadian Foreign Policy. Canada is most vigorous on issues of human rights when the rights in question are civil and political rather than economic and social, and when the offending regime is under Soviet rather than American influence. The contributors include: Frances Arbour, Victoria Berry, John W. Foster, Rhoda E. Howard, Kalmen Kaplansky, T.A. Keenleyside, Allen McChesney, Ronald Manzer, Robert O. Matthews, Stefania Szlek Miller, Cathal J. Nolan, Kim Richard Nossal, Cranford Pratt, Renate Pratt, Ernie Regehr, and H. Gordon Skilling.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHuman rights. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aArbour, Frances, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerry, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChesney, Allan MC, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoster, John W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoward, Rhoda E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaplansky, Kalmen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeenleyside, T.A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManzer, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatthews, Robert O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMi